4. Long Branches?

The dataset does not have Archaea.

INTERPRETATION #1: Are there any suspect branches in the raw, unrooted tree? Or does your tree look clean? Why or why not? The unrooted tree contains a very long branch extending to the right. This indicates that there are outlier ASVs with disproportionately high evolutionary distances compared to the rest of the tree. This could result from sequencing errors, chimeric sequences, or contamination.

BLAST

Now, copy and paste the ASV sequences into NCBIs Standard Nucleotide BLAST.

ASV_1878: No significant similarity found. But I choose to trust it! ASV_1910: Had an e-value of 0.0 and a percent identity of 97.94%, source matches the sample type here.

In conclusion, the tree looks legitimate and these are real bacterial ASVs. Therefore, I do not need to remove ASVs that were found in node 3159.

5. Root the Tree

5b. Midpoint Root

The projects data does not have archaea or a specified outgroup, it is possible to midpoint root the tree. I do not have archaea and have not removed the long branch, then I will follow the code below to midroot the tree.

6b. Merge phyloseq: Midpoint Rooted Tree

# Check to see if tree is rooted.. expect it to be false
is.rooted(phy_tree(unrooted_physeq))
## [1] FALSE
# Let's midpoint root the tree
midpoint_rooted_tree <- 
  unrooted_physeq %>%
  phy_tree() %>%
  phytools::midpoint.root()

# Is the new tree rooted? Should be TRUE!
is.rooted(midpoint_rooted_tree)
## [1] TRUE
# Assign to a new phyloseq object!
# Merge tree with the raw_preprocessed physeq
midpoint_rooted_physeq <-
  merge_phyloseq(raw_preprocessed_physeq, midpoint_rooted_tree)
## Found more than one class "phylo" in cache; using the first, from namespace 'phyloseq'
